COVID-19 and Religion

Sean McGoey

4/24/20

Objective

Analyzing available data to determine if there are any possible links between particularly religious areas and COVID-19 cases. We know that COVID is highly transmissible from person to person, and religious services bring millions of people together across the country every week (or at least they used to and they will again soon as states start to reopen). So lets take a look at whether theres any relationship.

Setup

First, well load our necessary packages.

# Load tidyverse, tidycensus, janitor, scales, mapview, ggthemes
library(tidyverse)
library(tidycensus)
library(janitor)
library(scales)
library(mapview)
library(ggthemes)

Then well load in county-level COVID-19 data from The New York Times and data from the Association of Religion Data Archives 2010 Religious Congregation Membership Study. (Ideally wed have newer religion data than 2010, but the survey is conducted every 10 years.) Well also grab shifted geodata from the census well use it to look at maps later.

# Read in NYT county data, and build "key" column
nyt_covid_county <- read.csv("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/nytimes/covid-19-data/master/us-counties.csv") %>%
  mutate(key = paste(county, state, sep = "|", collapse=NULL))

# Read in 2010 Religion Census data
rcms_religion_data <- read.csv("data/rcms_2010.csv") %>%
  clean_names() %>%
  rename(congregations_per_10k = congregations_per_10k_people)

# Define Census API Key
census_api_key("549950d36c22ff16455fe196bbbd01d63cfbe6cf")

# Load ACS variable definitions
acs_variables <- load_variables(2017, "acs5" )

# Pull in shifted geodata
county_geodata_shifted <- get_acs(geography = "county",
              variables = c("B01001_001"), geometry = TRUE, shift_geo = TRUE)

Next, because the NYT data is a cumulative set tracking the total number of cases/deaths every day rather than each days new count well pull out only the highest values to find the most updated totals.

# Group by key phrase in order to examine each county's case count peak to date
nyt_covid_county_max <- nyt_covid_county %>%
  filter(!is.na(fips)) %>%
  filter(!str_detect(county, "Unknown")) %>%
  group_by(key, county, state, fips) %>%
  summarise(case_peak = max(cases))

Then well join the table of max case counts to the religion census data and add a column for cases per 10K population.

county_covid_religion <- inner_join(nyt_covid_county_max, rcms_religion_data, BY=key) %>%
  select(key, fips, county, state, population, adherents, congregations, congregations_per_10k, religious_adherence, case_peak) %>%
  mutate(cases_per_10k = case_peak / population * 10000) %>%
  mutate(fips = toString(fips)) %>%
  mutate(fips = if_else(str_length(fips) == 4, paste("0", fips, sep="", collapse = NULL), fips))

# NOTE: Mutate functions convert fips from an int to a string and solves for leading 0s being omitted when formatted as numbers.

Well also build a table that allows us to look at variables on the map.

geo_county_covid_religion <- county_geodata_shifted %>%
 inner_join(county_covid_religion, by=c("GEOID" = "fips"))

First variable: Religious adherence

Were going to start by looking at the relationship between religious adherence and confirmed cases so far. Lets plot out some maps. First, per-capita COVID cases in each county across the country:

geo_county_covid_religion %>%
  ggplot(aes(fill = cases_per_10k)) +
  geom_sf(lwd = 0) +
  theme_map() +
  labs(fill='Confirmed cases per 10,000 people', caption = "Source: New York Times COVID-19 data") +
  scale_fill_continuous(labels = comma) +
  theme(legend.position="bottom") +
  scale_fill_viridis_c(option = "plasma",labels = comma)

A few well-defined hot spots around the country, but not necessarily much in the way of a pattern. Next, well look at religious adherence:

geo_county_covid_religion %>%
  ggplot(aes(fill = religious_adherence)) +
  geom_sf(lwd = 0) +
  theme_map() +
  labs(fill='% of religious adherents',caption = "Source: The Association of Religion Data Archives, 2010 survey") +
  scale_fill_continuous(labels = comma) +
  theme(legend.position="bottom") +
  scale_fill_viridis_c(option = "plasma",labels = comma)

Thats a much more defined pattern: Lots of adherents in the South, Midwest and Plains states, with a few other pockets around the country.

But we need more than just maps. Lets see if we can find an actual relationship between religious adherence and COVID cases so far.

ggplot(county_covid_religion) +
  geom_point(aes(religious_adherence, cases_per_10k)) +
  labs(x="Religious adherence %", y="Peak COVID cases per 10,000 people", caption = "Source: NYT COVID-19 data and the Association of Religion Data Archives", fill="key") +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = comma) +
  scale_x_continuous(labels = comma) + 
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1)) +
  geom_smooth(aes(religious_adherence, cases_per_10k), method = "lm", se = FALSE)

It doesnt look like theres much of a relationship; we can check that with a correlation test.

# Test the relationship
correlation_covid_adherents <- county_covid_religion %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  select(religious_adherence, cases_per_10k) 

cor.test(correlation_covid_adherents$religious_adherence, correlation_covid_adherents$cases_per_10k)
## 
##  Pearson's product-moment correlation
## 
## data:  correlation_covid_adherents$religious_adherence and correlation_covid_adherents$cases_per_10k
## t = 0.1017, df = 2840, p-value = 0.919
## alternative hypothesis: true correlation is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -0.03486205  0.03867361
## sample estimates:
##         cor 
## 0.001908357

Okay, so theres really nothing there to suggest that theres a link between the most religious counties in the U.S. and the cases of COVID-19 that have been confirmed so far. That makes some sense: according to mobile location tracking data from SafeGraph, church attendance is down an average of 76% nationwide since the first week of March, so places of worship have had limited opportunity to be spreading grounds.

Second variable: Concentration of religious adherents

What about another measure: not just the number of people who are adherents in a given county, but the concentration of those adherents? The ARDA data set includes a figure for congregations per 10,000 residents, which would help us assess whether areas with many different churches are more likely to have seen COVID outbreaks.

As we did with adherents, lets start with the maps. A quick reminder of the distribution of COVID cases:

geo_county_covid_religion %>%
  ggplot(aes(fill = cases_per_10k)) +
  geom_sf(lwd = 0) +
  theme_map() +
  labs(fill='Confirmed cases per 10,000 people', caption = "Source: New York Times COVID-19 data") +
  scale_fill_continuous(labels = comma) +
  theme(legend.position="bottom") +
  scale_fill_viridis_c(option = "plasma",labels = comma)

And now well map out congregations per 10,000 residents:

geo_county_covid_religion %>%
  ggplot(aes(fill = congregations_per_10k)) +
  geom_sf(lwd = 0) +
  theme_map() +
  labs(fill='Congregations per 10,000 residents',caption = "Source: The Association of Religion Data Archives, 2010 survey") +
  scale_fill_continuous(labels = comma) +
  theme(legend.position="bottom") +
  scale_fill_viridis_c(option = "plasma",labels = comma)

Still more congregations per 10K in the South/Plains areas fewer on the coasts and in major population centers.

Now were going to plot congregations per 10,000 against peak confirmed cases per 10,000.

ggplot(county_covid_religion) +
  geom_point(aes(congregations_per_10k, cases_per_10k)) +
  labs(x="Religious congregations per 10,000 people", y="Peak COVID cases per 10,000 people", caption = "Source: NYT COVID-19 data and the Association of Religion Data Archives", fill="key") +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = comma) +
  scale_x_continuous(labels = comma) + 
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1)) +
  geom_smooth(aes(congregations_per_10k, cases_per_10k), method = "lm", se = FALSE)

We can see a clearer pattern here than with the adherents its looking like there are actually higher COVID instances in counties with fewer congregations. Lets test the relationship:

# Test the relationship
correlation_covid_religion <- county_covid_religion %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  select(congregations_per_10k, cases_per_10k) 

cor.test(correlation_covid_religion$congregations_per_10k, correlation_covid_religion$cases_per_10k)
## 
##  Pearson's product-moment correlation
## 
## data:  correlation_covid_religion$congregations_per_10k and correlation_covid_religion$cases_per_10k
## t = -5.1736, df = 2840, p-value = 2.456e-07
## alternative hypothesis: true correlation is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -0.13292190 -0.06007163
## sample estimates:
##         cor 
## -0.09662618

So its not a strong correlation, but it is statistically significant. Counties where there are fewer congregations per 10,000 residents are slightly more likely to have already experienced coronavirus outbreaks. That makes some sense; fewer congregations means that the religious adherents in a given county are more concentrated into the same worship spaces.

Looking to the future

So maybe theres not a large correlation between religious adherence or congregations per 10,000 residents and confirmed COVID-19 cases to date. But that also makes some sense; as The Washington Post reported, mobile location data shows that stay-at-home orders were actually pretty effective at keeping churchgoers home on Easter one of the biggest attendance days of the year for Christian churches. But some states are starting to lift their stay-at-home orders, so is it possible that some counties could be vulnerable to new outbreaks once people start to return to churches?

Lets start by using what weve already looked at to identify a subset of counties: ones with high rates of religious adherence and lower numbers of congregations per 10,000 residents. How many of the ~2,800 counties in our current dataset are in the top 20% of religious adherents and the bottom 20% of congregations per 10K?

high_adherence_low_congregation <- county_covid_religion %>%
  filter(religious_adherence >= quantile(county_covid_religion$religious_adherence, probs = 0.80)) %>%
  filter(congregations_per_10k <= quantile(county_covid_religion$congregations_per_10k, probs = 0.20)) %>%
  select(fips, county, state, population, religious_adherence, congregations_per_10k, key) %>%
  arrange(desc(population))

high_adherence_low_congregation

There are some interesting spots here among the 34 results. We find several counties in Louisiana and surrounding New York City (Suffolk and Nassau on Long Island, Westchester to the immediate north, and Bergen and Union in New Jersey), two areas that are existing hot spots. We also find Fulton County in Georgia, which is home to the city of Atlanta and in a state that has already started reopening.

But which of these areas could be vulnerable as the hot spots of the future? Lets see what happens when we limit that list to places that are not already among the counties with the highest rates of COVID-19 cases:

high_adherence_low_congregation <- county_covid_religion %>%
  filter(religious_adherence >= quantile(county_covid_religion$religious_adherence, probs = 0.80)) %>%
  filter(congregations_per_10k <= quantile(county_covid_religion$congregations_per_10k, probs = 0.20)) %>%
  filter(cases_per_10k <= quantile(county_covid_religion$cases_per_10k, probs = 0.85)) %>%
  mutate(avg_congregation_size = population / congregations) %>%
  select(county, state, population, religious_adherence, congregations, avg_congregation_size, congregations_per_10k, fips, key) %>%
  arrange(congregations_per_10k)

high_adherence_low_congregation

Again, there a couple of interesting findings, like Bristol County, RI, which is a heavily Catholic county with an average congregation size of nearly 2,000 people. But it still might not be the best story.

Untangling COVIDs racial disparities

We know from [data provided by the CDC] (https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/need-extra-precautions/racial-ethnic-minorities.html) that COVID-19 has disproportionately affected black communities, both in terms of confirmed cases and deaths. Lets try some of this analysis again, but with a focus on heavily African American counties. We need to start by identifying those counties. At the 2010 census, 12.6% of the U.S. population reported as Black or African American, so lets use double that number 25% and up as a guidepost.

# Pull in African American population at county level
county_geodata_aa <- get_acs(geography = "county",
              variables = "B02001_003", geometry = TRUE) %>%
  rename(aa_pop=estimate)

# Join African American population to county table, filter on % African American >= 25
county_covid_religion_aa <- county_covid_religion %>%
  inner_join(county_geodata_aa, by=c("fips" = "GEOID")) %>%
  mutate(aa_percentage = aa_pop/population) %>%
  filter(aa_percentage >= .25)

Is there a stronger relationship between religious adherence and COVID cases in heavily African American counties?

ggplot(county_covid_religion_aa) +
  geom_point(aes(religious_adherence, cases_per_10k)) +
  labs(x="Religious adherence %", y="Peak COVID cases per 10,000 people", caption = "Source: NYT COVID-19 data and the Association of Religion Data Archives", fill="key") +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = comma) +
  scale_x_continuous(labels = comma) + 
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1)) +
  geom_smooth(aes(religious_adherence, cases_per_10k), method = "lm", se = FALSE)

And well test the correlation.

# Test the relationship
correlation_covid_adherents_aa <- county_covid_religion_aa %>%
  select(religious_adherence, cases_per_10k)

cor.test(correlation_covid_adherents_aa$religious_adherence, correlation_covid_adherents_aa$cases_per_10k)
## 
##  Pearson's product-moment correlation
## 
## data:  correlation_covid_adherents_aa$religious_adherence and correlation_covid_adherents_aa$cases_per_10k
## t = 0.35958, df = 405, p-value = 0.7194
## alternative hypothesis: true correlation is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -0.07947728  0.11486918
## sample estimates:
##        cor 
## 0.01786469

So theres still no serious connection between adherence and COVID in heavily African American counties. Lets check on the relationship between congregations per 10,000 and COVID.

ggplot(county_covid_religion_aa) +
  geom_point(aes(congregations_per_10k, cases_per_10k)) +
  labs(x="Congregations per 10,000 people", y="Peak COVID cases per 10,000 people", caption = "Source: NYT COVID-19 data and the Association of Religion Data Archives", fill="key") +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = comma) +
  scale_x_continuous(labels = comma) + 
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1)) +
  geom_smooth(aes(religious_adherence, cases_per_10k), method = "lm", se = FALSE)

And well test the correlation.

# Test the relationship
correlation_covid_congregations_aa <- county_covid_religion_aa %>%
  select(congregations_per_10k, cases_per_10k)

cor.test(correlation_covid_congregations_aa$congregations_per_10k, correlation_covid_congregations_aa$cases_per_10k)
## 
##  Pearson's product-moment correlation
## 
## data:  correlation_covid_congregations_aa$congregations_per_10k and correlation_covid_congregations_aa$cases_per_10k
## t = 0.073016, df = 405, p-value = 0.9418
## alternative hypothesis: true correlation is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -0.09360881  0.10079657
## sample estimates:
##         cor 
## 0.003628157

Conclusions

So it turns out that when we focus on heavily African American communities, we actually lose the slight negative correlation we had between number of congregations and COVID outbreaks nationwide.

There are a few outliers that I want to go back and look at, though. Lets redraw the nationwide plot of adherence vs.COVID:

ggplot(county_covid_religion) +
  geom_point(aes(religious_adherence, cases_per_10k)) +
  labs(x="Religious adherence %", y="Peak COVID cases per 10,000 people", caption = "Source: NYT COVID-19 data and the Association of Religion Data Archives", fill="key") +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = comma) +
  scale_x_continuous(labels = comma) + 
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1)) +
  geom_smooth(aes(religious_adherence, cases_per_10k), method = "lm", se = FALSE)

There appear to be about five or so counties with peaks above roughly 400 cases per 10,000 residents, and they come from different places on the scale of religious adherence:

# Filter down to counties with case peaks above 400 per 10,000 residents
county_covid_400 <- county_covid_religion %>%
  filter(cases_per_10k >= 400)

# Plot religious adherence against case peaks for those counties (no trend line)
ggplot(county_covid_400) +
  geom_point(aes(religious_adherence, cases_per_10k)) +
  labs(x="Religious adherence %", y="Peak COVID cases per 10,000 people", caption = "Source: NYT COVID-19 data and the Association of Religion Data Archives", fill="key") +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = comma) +
  scale_x_continuous(labels = comma) + 
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1))

Okay, so its five counties. Lets see what they look like when we plot cases against congregations instead:

# Plot congregations against case peaks for the five counties with cases per 10K >= 400 (no trend line)
ggplot(county_covid_400) +
  geom_point(aes(congregations_per_10k, cases_per_10k)) +
  labs(x="Congregations per 10,000 people", y="Peak COVID cases per 10,000 people", caption = "Source: NYT COVID-19 data and the Association of Religion Data Archives", fill="key") +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = comma) +
  scale_x_continuous(labels = comma) + 
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1))

Nothing in the single digits, but no outrageously high numbers either. Lets actually identify what the five counties are so we can do a little research and see if there are common threads connecting them:

county_covid_400 %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  select(county, state, population, religious_adherence, congregations_per_10k, case_peak, cases_per_10k) %>%
  arrange(desc(cases_per_10k))
